      "content": "The idea that segregation was necessary to protect public health was based on the pseudoscientific concept of \"racial hygiene.\" Proponents of segregation claimed that African Americans were more likely to spread diseases such as tuberculosis, syphilis, and malaria, which were prevalent in urban areas with high concentrations of minority populations. By separating these groups, they argued, public health would be improved, and the risk of disease transmission would be reduced.\n\nRegarding social order, segregationists claimed that mixed-race neighborhoods would lead to increased crime rates, vandalism, and social unrest. They argued that African Americans were more likely to engage in delinquent behavior, such as looting and arson, and that their presence in white neighborhoods would lead to a decline in property values and an increase in tensions between racial groups. By separating the two groups, segregationists believed that social order would be maintained, and the stability of white communities would be preserved.\n\nIn terms of property values, segregationists claimed that the presence of African Americans in a neighborhood would lead to a decrease in property values, as they believed that minority populations would drive up housing costs and reduce the quality of life for white residents. By separating the two groups, they argued, property values would be maintained, and the economic",
